ncholy tidings had been announced to our citizens, that the Governor of the State \u2013 the patriot and public-spirited [[DeWitt Clinton|''Clinton'']] had closed his mortal career\u2026[This prompted] a determination that the edifice which was about to be founded should be honored with his illustrious name.\u201d [[c:File:New-York Spectator 1829-07-24 p. 2.jpg|''New York Spectator'']] (July 24, 1829), p. 2 (section headed \u201cTuesday, July 21, 1829\u201d)</ref>\n<ref name=lec>[https://query.nytimes.com/search/query?query=%22mercantile+library%22&d=&o=&v=&c=&n=10&dp=0&daterange=period&srcht=a&year1=1851&mon1=09&day1=18&year2=1980&mon2=12&day2=31&srchst=p&sort=oldest Archive listing] at the ''[[New York Times]]'' website</ref>\n<ref name= emer>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1852/02/17/87828711.pdf \"Mercantile Library Lectures\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (February 17, 1852)</ref>\n<ref name=oliv>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1853/10/28/87872542.pdf \"Oliver Wendell Holmes commences...\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (October 28, 1853)</ref>\n<ref name=sold>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1854/06/01/75368321.pdf \"The Mercantile Library\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 1, 1854)</ref>\n<ref name=NYT1890>See\n*[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1890/07/17/103253289.pdf \u201cIn and About the City,\u201d] ''The New York Times'' (June 17, 1890)\n*[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1891/05/22/103308885.pdf \u201cFine Library Quarters,\u201d] ''The New York Times'' (May 22, 1891)\n*[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1891/11/10/103349711.pdf \u201cThe Mercantile Library,\u201d] ''The New York Times'' (November 10, 1891)</ref>\n<ref name=chap>[http://centerforfiction.org/building/ \"Our Building\"] at the Center for Fiction website Accessed: November 1, 2010</ref>\n<ref name=kopp>Koppel, Lily [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/03/nyregion/03mercantile.html?scp=3&sq=%22center+for+fiction%22&st=nyt \"Mercantile Library Moves, and Gets a Nudge Into the 21st Century\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 3, 2008)</ref>\n<ref name=konig>Konigsberg, Eric. [http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/05/23/historic-merc-library-will-move-fiction-or-fact/?scp=1-b&sq=%22center+for+fiction%22&st=nyt \"Historic Merc Library Will Move: Fiction, or Fact\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' City Room blog (May 23, 2008)</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Further reading'''\n:'''Issued by the Mercantile Library'''\n* {{citation |title=Annual report |url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/010064400 }} 1836, 1917, etc.;   [https://archive.org/stream/twentysecondannu00merc#page/n0/mode/2up 1843]\n* {{Citation |url = https://openlibrary.org/books/ia:constitutionbyla00merc/Constitution_by-laws_and_regulations_of_the_Mercantile_library_association_of_the_City_of_New_York. |title = Constitution, by-laws and regulations of the Mercantile Library Association of the City of New York |date = 1855 |publisher = Baker, Godwin & Co.  }}\n* {{citation |title=Constitution |year=1870 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KtgUR_hWe3kC }}\n\n:'''Catalogues'''\n* {{cite book |title=Catalogue of the books belonging to the Mercantile Library Association of the City of New-York |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=p5sQAAAAIAAJ |year= 1825}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/systematiccatalo00merciala#page/n5/mode/2up |title=Systematic Catalogue of Books in the Collection of the Mercantile Library Association of the City of New York  |year=1837 }}\n* [https://archive.org/stream/cataloguemercan01newgoog#page/n2/mode/2up 1844]\n* [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_OJI1AQAAIAAJ 1856]\n* {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/catalogueofbooks00mercrich#page/n5/mode/2up |title=Catalogue of Books in the Mercantile Library of the City of New York  |year=1866 }}\n* [https://archive.org/details/supplementtocat01newgoog 1869]\n* [https://archive.org/details/secondsupplemen01newgoog 1872]\n\n:'''About the Mercantile Library'''\n* {{cite book |author=E. Porter Belden |title=New York, Past, Present, and Future |location= NY |publisher= Prall, Lewis & Co. |year= 1850 |edition=3rd |chapter=Literature, Science, and Taste: Mercantile Library Association |chapterurl= https://archive.org/stream/newyorkpastprese1850beld#page/n137/mode/2up }}\n* {{Cite book |publisher = C.S. Francis & Co. |location = New York |title = Stranger's Hand-Book for the City of New York |date = 1854 |oclc = 8067569 |chapter=Literary Institutions: Mercantile Library Association |chapterurl= https://archive.org/stream/francissguidetoc01fran#page/72/mode/2up }}\n* {{citation |author=Edward Edwards |title=Memoirs of Libraries |location=London |year=1859 |volume=2 |page=198+ |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/memoirslibrarie00edwagoog#page/n240/mode/2up |chapter=Libraries of the United States |author-link=Edward Edwards (librarian) }}\n* {{Citation |publisher = J.S. Redfield |date = 1871 |location = New York |title = Redfield's Traveler's Guide to the City of New York |chapter=Mercantile Library |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/redfieldstravele01redf#page/86/mode/2up }}\n* {{citation |author= Jno. [John] R. G. Hassard |authorlink=John Rose Greene Hassard |date=February 1871 |title=The New York Mercantile Library |work=[[Scribner\u2019s Monthly]] |volume=1 |number=4 |pages= 353\u201367 |url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015035103277;view=1up;seq=365 }}\n* {{citation |title=Public Libraries in the USA |year=1876 |location=Washington DC |pages=928\u2013931 }}\n* {{Citation |publisher = New York History Co.|title = Memorial History of the City of New York |editor = James Grant Wilson |date = 1893 |volume=4 |pages=99\u2013102 |chapter=Libraries of New York: Mercantile Library |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/memorialhistoryo04wilsuoft#page/98/mode/2up }}\n* {{cite book |title=King's Handbook of New York City |edition= 2nd |year=1893 |publisher=[[Moses King]] |chapter=Mercantile Library |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=MEEAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA328 }}\n* {{cite book|author=New York Library Club |title=Libraries of Greater New York |location=NY |year=1902 |chapter=Mercantile Library Association of New York |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=0Ig-AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA49 }}\n* {{citation |last=Augst |first=Thomas |title=The Business of Reading in Nineteenth Century America: The New York Mercantile Library |journal=[[American Quarterly]] |volume= 50 |issue=2 |pages=267\u2013305 |year= 1998 |doi=10.1353/aq.1998.0007 }}\n* {{citation |title=Cultural Record Keepers: The New York Mercantile Library and Its Home Delivery Service |author= Larry T. Nix |journal= [[Libraries & the Cultural Record]] |volume= 42 |issue= 4 |pages= 452\u2013455 |year=2007 |jstor= 25549443 |doi= 10.1353/lac.2007.0063 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mercantile Library Association (New York City)}}\n* {{Official website|http://centerforfiction.org/}}\n* {{youtube|u=centerforfiction|Center for Fiction}}\n\n[[Category:Libraries in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Subscription libraries]]\n[[Category:Midtown Manhattan]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|40|45|22.93|N|73|58|38.23|W|display=title}} \n[[File:Mercantile Library at Astor Opera House crop.jpg|thumb|right|325px|The Mercantile Library in the [[Astor Opera House]] building, 1886]]\n\nThe '''Center for Fiction''', originally called the '''New York Mercantile Library''', is a [[not-for-profit]] organization in [[New York City]], with offices currently located at 15 Lafayette Avenue in Fort Greene, Brooklyn. Prior to their move in early 2018, The Center for Fiction was located at 17 [[47th Street (Manhattan)|East 47th Street]], between [[Madison Avenue (Manhattan)|Madison]] and [[Fifth Avenue (Manhattan)|Fifth]] Avenues in [[Midtown Manhattan]]. The Center works to promote fiction and literature and to give support to writers. It originated in 1820 as the (New York) Mercantile Library and in 2005 changed its name to the '''Mercantile Library Center for Fiction'''.<ref name=cff-history>{{cite web |url=http://centerforfiction.org/about/history/ |title=History |publisher=Center for Fiction |accessdate=February 9, 2014 }}</ref> although it presents itself as simply \"The Center for Fiction\".\n\nThe Center, which is one of 17 remaining membership libraries in the United States, three of which are in New York City,<ref name=nyt/> maintains a large circulating library of 20th and 21st century fiction, in addition to many stored volumes of 19th century fiction. It also stocks non-fiction volumes on subjects related to literature.<ref name=coll/> It maintains a Reading Room, operates a curated independent bookstore primarily featuring works of fiction, rents space to writers at low cost, and presents literary programs to the public.<ref name=aboutus /> The organization also awards the annual [[Center for Fiction First Novel Prize]].\n\n==Mercantile Library==\n===1820\u20131853===\n[[File:Mercantile Library ad.png|thumb|right|275px|From the ''New York Commercial Advertiser'' (November 2, 1820)]]\n\nThe foundation of the Mercantile Library Association was instigated by the New York [[Chamber of Commerce]],<ref name=gotham498/> which placed newspaper advertisements in November 1820 asking merchant clerks to meet at a local coffee house to discuss forming an organization based on the [[Mercantile Library Association (Boston, Massachusetts)|Mercantile Library]] in [[Boston]], which had been created earlier that year.<ref name=aboutus />  The purpose of the new organization was to provide the city's growing population of clerks with an alternative to what were considered to be immoral entertainments and other vices of the city.<ref name=gotham498 /><ref name=list/>\n\nThe Association's first subscription circulating library, which had 700 volumes<ref name=nytgray/> in rented rooms at 49 [[Fulton Street (Manhattan)|Fulton Street]] in [[Manhattan]], was open to most of the general public, but only merchant clerks were allowed to vote for and be officers in the Association.<ref name=enc-nyc />  By the year 1826, the financial \"prospects brightened to the extent that the officers hired a suite of rooms in the Harpers building on Cliff Street, and starting the reading room, which has continued to be an important part of the institution in all its successive homes.\u201d<ref name=hist/> In 1830, the library moved to a new building designed by architect Seth Geer, called Clinton Hall, at [[Nassau Street (Manhattan)|Nassau]] and Beekman Streets,<ref name=map/> which the Clinton Hall Association, made up of prominent members of the Mercantile Library Association, had raised funds to construct.<ref name=enc-nyc /> Frequent lectures were presented by the library,<ref name=lec/> including by [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]]&nbsp;<ref name= emer/> and [[Oliver Wendell Holmes, Sr.]].<ref name=oliv/>\n\nBy 1844 the library contained works of agriculture and gardening; amusements, games, sports &c; anecdotes, facetiae, table talk &c; Anglo Saxon language &c; antiquities, heraldry, mythology, and numismatics; architecture; arts and sciences; astronomy; banking and currency; bibliography and typography; biography; book keeping; botany; chemistry; commerce; [[conchology]]; dictionaries and [[lexicons]]; domestic economy; dramatic literature; education; electricity and magnetism; essays and literary miscellanies; fine arts; geography; geology and mineralogy; history; language; law; letters; mathematics; medicine; metaphysics; miscellaneous works; moral science; music; natural history; natural philosophy; novels; novels in foreign languages; orations, speeches and addresses; periodicals; [[phrenology]]; poetry; political economy; political science; religion; rhetoric, oratory and criticism; Shakspeare; slavery; voyages and travels; Africa, America, Asia, China, Egypt, England, Europe, France, Germany, Greece, India, Ireland, Italy, London, Rome, Russia, Scandinavia, Scotland, Spain and Portugal, Switzerland.<ref>{{citation |title=Catalogue of the Mercantile Library in New York |chapter=Classified Catalogue: List of Subjects |chapterurl= https://books.google.com/books?id=_mtMx5Z8J28C&pg=PA231 |year=1844 }}</ref>\n\nAmong its newspaper subscriptions in 1844 were the ''Churchman'', ''[[Evening Post (New York)|Evening Post]]'', ''Examiner'', ''[[Journal of Commerce]]'', ''[[Morning Courier and New-York Enquirer|Morning Courier]]'', ''New York American'', ''[[Commercial Advertiser|New York Commercial Advertiser]]'', ''New York Evangelist'', ''New York Observer'', ''[[New York Tribune]]'', ''[[Niles Weekly Register]]'', and ''[http://www.worldcat.org/title/noticioso-de-ambos-mundos/oclc/43898018 Noticioso de Ambos Mundos]''.<ref name=1844periodicals>{{citation |title=Catalogue of the Mercantile Library in New York |chapter=Classified Catalogue: Periodicals |chapterurl= https://books.google.com/books?id=_mtMx5Z8J28C&pg=PA270 |year=1844 }}</ref> Among the library's magazine subscriptions in 1844 were: ''[[Ainsworth's Magazine]]'', ''American Journal of Science and the Arts'', ''American Phrenological Journal'', ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/008717775 American Rail Road Journal]'', ''[[Annals and Magazine of Natural History]]'', ''Athenaeum'', ''[[Bentley's Miscellany]]'', ''[[Blackwood's Magazine]]'', ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000520355 British and Foreign Review]'', ''[[Chambers's Edinburgh Journal]]'', ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000530952 Chemical Gazette]'', ''[[Christian Examiner]]'', ''[[Dublin University Magazine]]'', ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/006062092 Eclectic Museum of Foreign Literature]'', ''[[Eclectic Review]]'', ''[[Edinburgh Review]]'', ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000531108 Foreign Quarterly Review]'', ''[[Franklin Institute]]'s Journal'', ''Frazer's Magazine'', ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/008607042 Gardener's Magazine]'', ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'', ''[[Graham's Magazine]]'', ''[[The Knickerbocker|Knickerbocker]]'', ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/006890820 Ladies Companion]'', ''[[The Mechanics' Magazine|Mechanic's Magazine]]'', ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000057181 Merchants Magazine]'', ''[[The Metropolitan Magazine|Metropolitan Magazine]]'', ''Mirror'', ''[[The Nautical Magazine|Nautical Magazine]]'', ''[[New Monthly Magazine]]'', ''[[Penny Magazine]]'', ''[[Philosophical Magazine]]'', ''Phrenological Journal'', ''[[Quarterly Review]]'', ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/006109532 Repertory of Patent Inventions]'', ''[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/00892368 Sailor's Magazine]'', ''[[Southern Literary Messenger]]'', ''[[Tait's Edinburgh Magazine]]'', ''United Service Journal'', ''[[United States Magazine and Democratic Review]]'', and ''[[Westminster Review]]''.<ref name=1844periodicals />\n\nIn addition to reading materials, as of the 1850s the Association owned \"a [[Cabinet of curiosities|cabinet]] of minerals and shells, a collection of revolutionary medals, miscellaneous coins, various paintings, statue of the 'Dancing Girl Reposing', [[Minerva]], and a [[Bust (sculpture)|bust]] of Philip Stone.<ref>{{Citation |publisher = J.B. Lippincott & Co. |location = Philadelphia |title = Manual of Public Libraries, Institutions, and Societies in the United States |ol = 6937678M |author = William Jones Rhees |date = 1859 |chapter=New York: Mercantile Library Association |chapterurl= https://archive.org/stream/cu31924029528951#page/n309/mode/2up |pages=277\u2013287}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Reading room, Mercantile Library Association, New York City.png|thumb|left|275px|Reading room, Mercantile Library Association, New York City, circa 1871]]\n\n===1854-1960s===\nBy 1853, the Association had over 4,000 members<ref>Burrows & Wallace, p.733</ref> and over 30,000 volumes, and in 1854, the library moved again, this time uptown to the [[Astor Opera House]] building on [[Lafayette Street (Manhattan)|Lafayette Street]] between [[Astor Place]] and [[8th Street (Manhattan)|East 8th Street]].<ref name=enc-nyc />  The opera house had closed its doors as a result of the [[Astor Place riot]] of 1849, and the building was sold for $140,000<ref name=sold/> to the Association, which renamed it \"Clinton Hall\" and moved the library there as a place which was more convenient to its members.<ref name=enc-nyc />  At its new location, the Association offered classes and public lectures, including by [[Frederick Douglass]], [[William Thackeray]], and [[Mark Twain]],<ref name=aboutus/> and functioned as a cultural center.<ref name=enc-nyc />\n\nMembership during this period reached at least 12,000, while the library itself amassed 120,000 volumes, making it the largest circulating library in the United States at the time.<ref name=enc-nyc>Pascu</ref> By 1872 the library contained works of biography; history, geography and travels; literature; mathematics; medical science; mental and moral science; natural sciences; political science; the arts; and theology.<ref>{{citation |chapter=Synopsis of the Classified Index |title=Second Supplement to the Catalogue of Books |publisher=Mercantile Library Association |location=NY |year=1872 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=YzCN_ItU-7EC&pg=PA159 }}</ref> However, because the library did not stay open late at night, its services were not generally available to the working class, a deficit which was remedied when the [[Cooper Union]] opened a block east on Astor Place: its reading room was open until 10 p.m.<ref>Burrows & Wallace, p.782</ref>\n\nIn 1891, requiring more space, the Association tore down the opera house and replaced it with an 11-story building designed by [[George E. Harney]],<ref name=aia4>{{cite AIA4}}</ref> which it also named \"Clinton Hall\".  The new building featured a reading room on the top floor that was two stories high,<ref name=nytgray /><ref name=NYT1890/> and was to remain the headquarters for its library operations, which included 7 branches, until 1920, when it relocated to rented space.<ref name=nytgray /> However, in 1932, the library once again had its own building, at 17 [[47th Street (Manhattan)|East 47th Street]], designed by Henry Otis Chapman.<ref name=nytgray /><ref name=chap/> Here, the Association maintained its 230,000 volumes to serve 3,000 subscribers.<ref name=nytgray /><ref name=enc-nyc /> The library at this time still had branches at 149 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] at Liberty Street and 598 Madison Avenue at [[57th Street (Manhattan)|57th Street]].<ref name=nytgray />\n\n===1970s\u20132000s===\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1    = Clinton Hall Mercantile Library Bldg 13 Astor Place.jpg\n | width1    = 215\n | caption1  = 11-story Clinton Hall building replaced the Opera House as headquarters. In later years it was the Chinese consulate,<ref>Brozan, Nadine [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/06/realestate/postings-triangular-site-21-astor-place-50-ultramodern-condominiums-behind.html?scp=7&sq=%22mercantile+library%22&st=nyt \"Postings: On a Triangular Site at 21 Astor Place; 50 Ultramodern Condominiums Behind an Exterior From 1890\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (April 6, 2003)</ref> a union headquarters, the Astor Place Hotel, an office building, and, currently, condominiums.\n | image2    = Mercantile Library 17 E47 jeh.jpg\n | width2    = 145\n | caption2  = The Center for Fiction's headquarters at 17 [[47th Street (Manhattan)|East 47th Street]], which it sold sometime after 2008.<ref name=timesbrooklyn/>\n}}\n\nMembership in the library declined through the following decades, and the library sold off parts of its collection in the 1970s. \"In 1971 the theological collection was sold, in 1977 the foreign language collection was sold.\"<ref name=nytgray /> It also attempted a merger with [[Pace College]], but this did not occur. By 1987 the library was in financial distress, and closed for the summer of 1987, and then indefinitely in 1989, at a time when its membership was only 375 people.  The Association subsequently reorganized and reopened, with a new focus on fiction and literature.\n\nIn 1998, the ground floor of the building was renovated by [[Beyer Blinder Belle]].<ref name=nytgray /> The library \u2013 colloquially known as \"The Merc\" \u2013 had considered moving to a new location in 2008,<ref name=kopp/><ref name=konig/> but subsequently decided to remain at its historic Midtown Manhattan location.\n\n==Center for Fiction, 2005\u2013present==\nSince 2005 known as The Center for Fiction,<ref name=cff-history /> the organization presents a diverse program of free or low-cost public events, featuring over 100 authors, translators, and critics each year.  The Center also offers reading groups and writing workshops, open to the public, led by writers and scholars.\n\nIn May 2018, the organization announced that it would be moving its headquarters to a new building in [[downtown Brooklyn]] called Caesura and designed by Dattner Architects, a {{convert|17,500|sqft|m2|adj=on}} The space includes a library, classrooms, a writers studio, an auditorium for 160 people, a bookstore and a cafe. The three-story building will be co-owned with the [[Mark Morris Dance Group]] and a real estate company, which will have their own spaces there. The Center for Fiction was designed by Julie Nelson, Partner at  BKSK Architects LLP and opened in 2019.<ref name=timesbrooklyn>Libbey, Peter (May 4, 2018) [https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/04/books/new-brooklyn-home-of-center-for-fiction-to-open-in-2019.html \"New Brooklyn Home of Center for Fiction to Open in 2019\"] ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nThe Center bestows a number of awards annually:\n\n* The [[Clifton Fadiman|Fadiman]] Medal honors a book by a living American author that \"deserves renewed recognition and a wider readership\".\n* The Christopher Doheny Award goes to a writer of fiction or nonfiction, on the topic of serious illness, where the author has personal experience.\n* The [[Center for Fiction First Novel Prize|First Novel Prize]] is awarded to the best debut novel of the year. The 2014 winner was Tiphanie Yanique for ''Land of Love and Drowning''. The 2015 winner was Viet Thanh Nguyen for ''[[The Sympathizer]]''.\n* [[Maxwell E. Perkins]] Award is a life-time award to an editor, publisher, or agent who has \"discovered, nurtured, and championed\" writers of fiction. Daniel Halpern received the award for 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|title=ArtsBeat: Daniel Halpern, Founding Editor of Ecco, Still Inspired by Poetry |date=December 8, 2015 |publisher=Archy Nety |url=http://www.archynety.com/artsbeat-daniel-halpern-founding-editor-of-ecco-still-inspired-by-poetry/}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mercantile Library (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Mercantile Library Association (Boston, Massachusetts)]]\n*[[New York Public Library]]\n*[[Astor Library Building]]\n\n==References==\n'''Bibliography'''\n*{{cite gotham}}\n*Pascu, Elaine Weber. \"Mercantile Library Association\" in {{cite enc-nyc}}, p.&nbsp;750\u2013751\n\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=nyt>Eisenberg, Anne. [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/11/business/yourmoney/11library.html?scp=1&sq=%22center+for+fiction%22&st=nyt \"Libraries of Gracious Reading, for Members Only\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 11, 2006)</ref>\n<ref name=coll>[http://centerforfiction.org/collection/ \"Collection\"] at the Center for Fiction website. Accessed: November 1, 2010</ref>\n<ref name=aboutus>[http://centerforfiction.org/about/ \"Mission & History\"] at the Center for Fiction website Accessed: November 1, 2010</ref>\n<ref name=gotham498>Burrows & Wallace, p. 498</ref>\n<ref name=list>For additional context, see: [[List of libraries in 19th-century New York City]]</ref>\n<ref name=hist>Tomassi, Noreen. [http://centerforfiction.org/about/history/ \u201cA Hi